ce:section.ce:para:
To evaluate the effectiveness of this method compared to traditional HPLC with ultraviolet detection (HPLC-UV) for the detection of PMB in clinical serum samples, spiked recovery experiments were conducted by adding standard concentrations of PMB (0, 0.5, 1.5, and 3.0 μg/mL) to serum. As summarized in Table 1
                        , the spike recovery rates ranged from 84.59 % to 95.53 %, with relative standard deviations (RSDs) between 1.17 % and 3.82 %. The fluorescence-based method produced results that closely matched those obtained via HPLC-UV, demonstrating its accuracy and reliability. To further confirm the method's applicability, 20 clinical serum samples were collected, processed, and analyzed using the s-GQDs-AM@MIP platform. The PMB concentrations measured with this method were consistent with those obtained through HPLC/MS analysis (Table 2
                        ). These findings point towards the platform’s capability to accurately detect trace amounts of PMB in complex biological matrices (Fig. S5 and Fig. S6).
